19:<I have been so frustrated with students who say that can't do something and then throw up their hands. Additionally, I have had support teachers who also believe that a student can't do something and give them the okay to throw up their hands. I would love to share some of the information this information with parents, teachers and students. Recently, I have become focused on standards based grading, students revising their work and moving away from percentage grades. One reason being their focus on the grade. "Mrs. <nameRedac_anon_screen_name_redacted>, how can I get a 90% because right now I have an 89%. I want to be on high honors." Rarely, is there a mention of wanted to learn more. One idea which has popped into my mind is asking students to reflect more on what they have learned. I think of the KWL organizers that are so common in the schools and not so common in my class. I now see a value of completing this out with students so they can reflect on what they have learned and less on a grade. A job for me now? Integrate other ways in which I can move away from the fixed mindset of grading and more into a growth mindset. Maybe making some purchases from Vistaprint to focus on positive learning feedback is a step:)>
20:<I have been thinking of the two interventions shared so far with the "I believe in you" statement and the goal writing at the beginning of the year. I am thinking in math to have my students come up with three goals they have for math this year. This would be a graded assignment (turned in with three goals math related 100%) 

Then I could at the end of the year have them reflect on how they did on reaching these goals and can use the goals as a conversation to check in with them throughout the year. 
I think that will give the students some say in their math learning as well as helping me help the student reach their math goals for the year. And letting them know that I care about what they want to learn as well :)

I have also in the past had students send me word problems that they created and used them with permission in a live lesson on story problems which gave them a feeling of ownership as well in the class.>
