27:<You asked me, "How surprised are you by the information and data I have just presented?"

Not in the slightest. Data is regularly used to convey emotional responses, from numbers that should seem shocking to most, but to some of us, not at all. I shouldn't be shocked as much as I should be disappointed. Somewhere (for these students in the study) they are being forgotten. I don't want to place blame, basically because I cannot say with certainty where it should be placed. But in a first-world country, the American government should be ashamed to say that over 90% of students can't pass a 2-year College program because of 1 course. 


Next you asked me to answer the question, "How does this connect, if at all, with your own students or your own reason for taking this course?"

Well, for my opinions stated above is the precise reason that I connect  with this course. I am a first year teacher, so in fact I am 'Greener" than most students. I hope to gain some knowledge about pedagogy, strategies in the class, and resources to help me growth as an 'Educator'.  But mostly, and maybe truthfully, I hope to hear stories that make me cry, laugh and reflect about why Math(s) is both a challenge for some, and a strength for others. I really want to approach teaching Math as an opportunity for everyone...including, no scratch that, especially me:)>
