80:<Jumping in here... keep in mind the words "perhaps" -- as in, probably not... and "very specific LD" -- as in, most of the LDs out there *won't* preclude it. 
    I have a nephew with severe dysgraphia who's also pretty gifted in math - uses Efofex to get those problems down and yes, they have to battle with the schools sometimes... and I've had some years teaching folks with LDs, including at a small school with a visiting expert from the UK who wrote books about dyslexia and math... it's totally possible to raise a Math success :) (Warning:  most materials, esp. online, aren't particularly helpful, though...) I'd be glad to share resources  (I've got a few things on my site at www.resourceroom.net that I put there 'cause I didn't want them in a drawer, and I write in a blog at http://resourceroomblog.wordpress.com )>
81:<S0me free advice (probably worth every penny ;)) -- I'd suggest taking it slowly... *and* doing as much hands-on and concrete.   Have you seen David Berg's materials/approach?   (His actual training is lengthy and expensive, but I learned a lot just from http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4kJRyMC5HGs  and some of the other videos he has online).   So I would use a *lot* of pennies for practicing dividing.  Some of the free exercises at the dreambox.com website are also a lot of fun and low-stress, and might give you other ideas.   (I'm not trying to sell anything -- just share ideas that *might* help).   
