90:<I think students have been misguided about math. People say only smart kids can do math and saying this to a child you are setting him/her up for failure. I have a middle school daughter (8th grade) who hates math. She was going to take the California Mathematics State Exam and told me "I am going to score far below basic." It took me two weeks to break down the math and explain it to her. Long story short, she scored proficient on the state exam :) ! She gained confidence afterwards.>
91:<That sounds like a good plan! I work at the high school level and it is so important that math students have the courage to attempt a problem...fear of making a mistake can be immobilizing. It is true outside of the classroom too, as adults we need to tackle numerous problems that involve math. 
I can see you will now encourage your students' brains to grow. :)>
92:<I actually posted to FB today mentioning that commiserating with you child by saying you are not good at math either is not really an effective bonding experience and that studies show they will do worse than if you approach math with interest and anticipation of the excitement in learning along with your child.  - 4 young mothers thanked me  :)>
93:<As a kid, I struggled with math conceptually as well as forumlaically (I'm making that word up to describe that I lacked skill in math procedures -mostly due to a need for memorization of numbers).  Math didn't "click" for me until I was learning how to teach it in my teacher prep program in college.  But when it did...WOW!  As a teacher, it became really important to me to help my students approach math without fear and with excitement -I just knew that in order to learn, they needed to be engaged with their hearts.  My mom's favorite story is how she told my former high school math tutor that I LOVE to teach math and the look of shock on my tutor's face.  Hey, if I could learn algebra...anyone can!  It's been a sort of quest of mine to bring the wonder of math to my own children as well as the learners I work with.  I've been an educator in the US for over 20 years -public school, private school and most recently, home schooling my own two kiddos (6th and 8th grades this year). So...that's my background and what I'll base my answers on.  

I think that two factors are key to the question here - teaching methods and lack of foundational skills.  I think that traditional "top down" teaching methods are problematic.  We tend to teach math as linear (it's often not), overly formulaic (it's sometimes not or not necessary) and we come at it as if the key to math is in the rote memorization of facts and figures.  In fact, mathematics is ART.  Mathematics should be DISCOVERED, not directed -especially in the early years when kids are forming their perceptions and training their brains.  I also think that a lack of foundational skills can shake an already rocky self-perception of mathematical ability.  I'm not advocating for skill drills, though.  When I talk about lack of foundational skills, I'm really saying that people lack an understanding of concept, patterns, flow.  If kids learned to SEE math, rather than memorize math, they would have the foundational skills they need later on to actually build the skills.

Joyful learning :)>
