98:<The most damaging negative messages about math that stay with us are ones from our own parents and family members. Comments that excuse students from trying because it is just too hard for them: Smother love: Sympathy and protection from real life math experiences because they are just too young to have to do deal with money exchanges on their own: Laughter, ridicule  and derision in the guise of "I was just joking!" after a negative comment such as "It's easy . Just do it." or a quick snide remark in passing like "Dummy!" by a much admired big brother. 

PEER Pressure: It is very popular to say  "I hate Math!" with no specific reasons to support the statement except that it is the "cool" thing to say to be in the 'in group' crowd:Put downs by both the students who consider themselves superior, and the ones who just like being verbal bullies: Fear of being wrong publicly and admitting that you do not get it: Fear of asking for help.

Teachers: By grouping in ability levels:  by using comments in the classroom that are  heard and interpreted as negative; and the greatest damage is done by using the word "Fail" and the letter "F on graded assignments!>
