104:<I agree that the information (that mistakes are learning opportunities that directly lead to brain growth and to enhanced learning) is important and should be shared with educators and students.  But I don't understand your point that  making mistakes is currently experienced as a very bad thing and whether that taken into account in the research.  Yes, many kids experience mistakes this way.  Those with a fixed mindset take it as evidence that they are not capable.  However, those with a growth mindset just keep plugging a long.  So the fact that some students find mistakes excruciating is part of the problem - their fixed mindset is limiting the learning opportunity in that moment of error. The research encompasses this sad paradox.  The mistake itself is neutral.  What the student (or teacher) does with it -- that's what matters.  I like your lead in sentence to your essay. It made me laugh.  :-)>
