115:<Simple- overall it appears to be a cultural problem. We allow ourselves as adults and even as young children think that it's o.k. not to be "good at math." You hear excusable phrases like "I don't do math," or "math doesn't run in my family" all the time. We don't think twice thus the heavily relied belief that math is inherently innate. Similarly, we usually wouldn't say "I can't read" even if we weren't great readers. Asian countries believe innate ability is mostly hard work. American's believe split between DNA and how you apply yourself. But wait...is there also still a gender stereotype that boys are better at math? It has been suggested that effective teaching can help but we must also look at "the belief systems that influence children’s motivation." 

However, I still agree that we as teachers need to teach many different methods of math. As a child I loved math, but was never taught how to use math in the real world setting. I mean do you really see people today breaking out their pen and pencil to find the average price of their favorite Miss Me jeans after a 33% sale?  Problem solving was complete the even or odd numbered set of questions (which ever didn't have the solutions) in the back of the text for homework after watching the teacher/ students practice on the board. I didn't learn relevant "mental" problem solving until I was out of college and started my own life!! Why did I have to discover this on my own so late? Isn't life all about problem solving? I also believe part of the solution (at least at the elementary level) is an inquiry or self discovery based approach, not always giving the answers upfront. Teaching math must provide many relevant, manipulative experiences in which students may connect to a myriad of possibilities. Why does math have to be daunting? It should be FUN! :) <nameRedac_anon_screen_name_redacted>>
