117:<Do y'all use some sort of positive behavior incentives to reward students for good attendance or proper behavior?  We do at our school, and it seems to encourage some of them to strive to meet our expectations.  Of course, the ultimate goal is for them to do these things based on intrinsic motivation rather than external motivation, but we've got to start somewhere! :)>
118:<I still remember the anxiety I experienced in the third grade when my teacher gave us flash card tests on basic math facts (and I am in my 50's!). I've always been fairly good in math, but hate being timed or rushed. It seems as though those flash cards would go up and down faster than I could read them, much less jot down what I was instructed to write (I also wore glasses and had trouble seeing, so that may have been part of the problem) - I don't remember if we were supposed to copy the problems or just write down our answers. I just remember the sick feeling I would get in the pit of my stomach! That's one reason why I hate "timed tests" of any kind for my students! I don't want them to experience anxiety related to math because they are fearful of the time constraints! Unfortunately, we are required by higher authorities to provide them with testing situations similar to standardized tests so that they will develop test-taking skills to help them score the best they can. :( That's one dilemma I'm hoping to resolve during this course! :)>
