147:<Perpetual Pursuit of Perseverance and Perfection

I want to teach my students to embrace the mistakes, and see through the mistakes as a means to grow and learn. I will definitely inform the students that the brain learns more from a mistake, pointing out more synapses are formed more through the mistakes than through getting something right the first time. I really like the idea of actually having 5 students put work on the board, and telling them that at least one of them should intentionally make a mistake. This allows the struggling student to feel less afraid of making a mistake. Once all 5 problems are worked out on the board, I discuss with the class the work and ask them to find where the mistakes are (either deliberate, or accidental). 

One other mini-lesson I may add to my curriculum is a weekly highlight of a mistake that led to something snazzy.
http://science.discovery.com/famous-scientists-discoveries/10-accidental-inventions.htm

TL;DR: 1. Penicillin, 2.Pacemaker, 3. Synthetic Dye, 4. Radioactivity, 5. Plastic, 6. Rubber, 7. Teflon, 8. Coke, 9. "Smart Dust" (Tiny silicon sensors) 10. Saccharin>
