160:<I visualised the cases rising from the bottom, with a broader base being introduced each time to "support" the cases above it. From this point of view, I didn't see the now quite obvious (n squared + <zipRedac>) formula, but because I was focused on the added "base", I saw each new base simply as 2n + <zipRedac>, which then needed to be added to the previous case to determine the current case. I then copied the formulas down to row <zipRedac>00 in Excel, where (2 x <zipRedac>00) + <zipRedac> + <zipRedac>0000 (the 99th case) = <zipRedac>020<zipRedac>. In hindsight it seems a bit convoluted, but I suppose it illustrates how there are different methods (and tools) one can use to solve a problem . . . liked this one! ;)>
161:<Hi Katrien, 

I have just been preparing a training session which features this. Try this example (practically). Draw a rectangle and divide in half using a line from top to bottom. Now divide the left side into quarters using two diagonal lines and the right hand side into quarters using a vertical line and a horizontal line. You have now divided your shape into eighths which are all equal in size but not in shape. Hope this helps :)

Best wishes, <nameRedac_anon_screen_name_redacted>>
