190:<... yup, this is a toughie! 

I'll be collaborating this fall in a pre-pre-algebra course... word problems are a honking big deal. THey've had years and years of, when they *had* to do 'em, saying "okay, what math was in this section?  Let's find the numbers, do that math to it and put that down."  Usually that works for half of 'em, and no quiz is ever all word problems, so ... they can pass.
    Welcome to college.
    
    We'll start with reading a problem wiht the answers in it, and making a number sentence from it.  To wit:

The perimeter of a triangle is the distance around it.   THis triangle's sides are 4, 8, and 9 centimeters.   Its perimeter is 21 centimeters.

Draw that out and write a number sentence to say what's happening there.   (I may throw in irrelevant numbers at some point... but building confidence is my priority.)  
................... once they've got this little guy under their collective belts...

Okay, what if something changes?   What could you change in that triangle?
(make it visual -- lots of these folks are not focused on remembering what perimeter is; just how to get the math problem right.) 

If this side is (shorter, longer, whatever)... what happens to the perimeter?   (show the walk around...)  Does it make sense?   How does it make sense?   (connect the language and the visual and the numbers in the brain...) 
 
Can you make a new number sentence -- that is still true?   
If it's not true, why?   Let's figure it out. 
Okay... have fun with this... draw for me... try some different changes.   Let's make some more number sentences.  Get together with your buddy and see what you can come up with.  Impress me!   

Then let's talk about which things worked... and which things didn't... and why... 

We could also do a problem with something like traveling down a road, which we would draw, and we'd ride our first leg, which is in Mahomet 11 miles, and then to Monticello, which is another 17 miles, for our grand total of 38 miles.   We can make a number sentence out of that... and then do the same "make changes" process (if you take a longer route or find a short cut ;)). 

Then if we get *really* daring, I can say:  "Hey.  What if I changed the perspective.   We're *in* Mahomet.    We've done 11 miles.  It's 17 miles from here to Monticello, for a total of 38 miles.  Can we make a number sentence that *doesn't* have adding?   Can it still make sense?  What question would we be answering?>
