204:<I wonder how this would work.  We do the standard test (untimed and ungraded, of course), and then we gather up all of the tests, and then we find all of the mistakes that were made because of using an ineffective approach (skip over the ones that were simple arithmetic errors).  We make a new test, asking the students why the given answer is wrong.  It would be hard to do this with elementary arithmetic, but it could work for more complex problems.

The student would be asked to identify what was done to lead to the wrong answer, and then present a different approach (which can be a simple modification or an entirely new approach) that answers the question correctly.  This second part would be what they are graded on, not the first.  Credit would be given for a good idea that's still wrong.

I'm not certain if we would need to give each question to the student who made the mistake, but this approach would have the added effect that we don't waste time on areas that the students already know.

We can take it a step further.  We take the original test, find all of the questions that everyone got right, and we replace those with harder questions.  Then we start from the beginning with the new modified test.

Just an idea.  Maybe I, ahem, made a mistake . . .  :)>
