215:<I have struggled for a long time trying to group students within a class period (I teach High School) for collaborative activities.  Sometimes heterogeneous groups lead to stronger students "taking over" and doing most of the work, sometimes leaving struggling students "in the dust".  At other times heterogeneous groups have worked well where students have worked together and all members help each other understand the process before moving forward.  Homogeneous groups sometimes backfire if the weaker students just give up and can't see a wait to start while stronger students are done with the activity very quickly.

Now, after hearing about the research, I'm thinking that heterogeneous groups are the way to go.  I just need to learn better strategies for helping my students collaborate.  

20+ years in education and still learning!  :-)>
