218:<Unless there is a foundation of Game Theory, Graph Theory and Number Theory in schools, then our schools will continue to flounder in creating disconnected topics riddled with boring syntax and horrible "applications".  There also has to be a viable and student-friendly bridge between arithmetic and algebra, where the generalization starts to occur with simplicity and curiosity--ie) The sum of three odd numbers always equals an ______ number.  And, without having a rich history of the subject in some kind of thematic coherence, any mathematics taught will be without color.
Too much emphasis on correctness.  We need to spend more time discussing problems that we as teachers cannot solve/didn't solve with our students.  The disarming of the anxiety in the classroom begins with honesty about our own mortal ability with the subject:)>
