226:<. 
    I remember reading about this in _What's Math Got To Do With It_, and I, too, wanted to figure out some way to convey this to the rest of the world so they'd understand it, because these "uncompressed math" learners and so many of their teachers assume that they just can't get fluent...
      I think, perhaps, that Sebastian hasn't been in the minds of an awful lot of folks, though.   He assumes that they're "mathing" things when... no, not necessarily.   Lots of functional citizens *don't* engage in even the basic mathy stuff.  To them, it *isn't* all addition with flair, compressed and elaborated.   Lots of 'em have forgotten the addition in their avoidance of that nasty stuff called math. 
      I was having some students review a video lesson from Algebra2go ( http://www.saddleback.edu/faculty/lperez/algebra2go/ ) about perimeter, and adding numbers, and one student thought the *best* part of the video was when he reminded the students (from a previous lesson these folks hadn't seen) that they could do "Kung Fu Math" and put the easy-combo numbers together first and then do the rest.  In our pre-pre-algebra course, we're going to do a *lot* of building those "tricks" -- and why they work ... ifI can find time to build those lessons in the next three weeks ;) 
     Another one of my ladies, this morning, was wrapping her mind around the connection between multiplying by a half, taking half of something, and dividing by two.   Watching her shift from the calculator to figuring out mentally that if the diameter is 206, the radius is 103, warmed the cockles of my heart :)
    We put together a sort of "crash course in concepts" last spring, borrowing from Dorothea Steinke's "part and whole" work ( http://www.ncsall.net/index.php@id=70.html has the link to a neat article about it) and Marilyn Burn's math concept inventory ( https://mathreasoninginventory.com   ) .   Oh, my, the number of people who "used the standard algorithm" for, say, 1000 - 997... mentally! That analogy of the ladder is painfully valid.  Even with just seven sessions, they were more successful when they dove into pre-algebra (hence our hope that a full semester of conceptual preparation for pre-algebra will have an even better effect).>
