246:<In my school we do not split students into ability groups for mathematics, but it is common practice for reading.  The research on grouping and its detrimental effects made a lot of sense, but I wonder how it would apply to language education.  However, since this course is about math, I'll stick to that!  Rather than group for mathematics, at my school we are encouraged to offer parallel questions.  When doing problem solving, we give 2 similar problems- one that might be more challenging, and one that might be slightly simpler- and give the students the option of which problem to choose.  Often the students will go for the more challenging problem.  :)>
