248:<My name is <nameRedac_anon_screen_name_redacted>.  
I was 16 and enrolled in a high school third grade class in a north Italy city.  
I was a bit lazy and busy with other interests so I wasn't studying much, and therefore one of the lower grade student in English.  

One of my best fried was Nick, born in USA from Italian parents, almost as good in speaking, reading and writing English as a mother language one.  
One day our official teacher of English class had to go in hospital for two months and a substitute was coming to teach us English. 
She, the new teacher, could know us only by reading the notes of the official teacher, previous grades and votes.
 
Nick and I had the idea to exchange: I was him and he was me.... and of course the whole class was aligned ....  

Can someone imagine the results ?    

  :)

The consideration I wish to share with all of you is not so much the fact that the "new" <nameRedac_anon_screen_name_redacted> was doing rather well in English (In reality was Nick), but the fact that the "new" Nick was doing well in English, too. 

In other words I "improved" quite a lot my English performances "just" by changing my name or, in other words, changing the "ideas", "opinions", "past performances" which such name was representing in the head of a new teacher who based on written records.
 
Apart from the fun of it, it could be an example of how big a role preconceptions, prejudice and bias have in the teacher - student relationship.   

Hope you liked the experiments. Please comment if you wish so.

Bye

m.>
