256:<I thought about the "driving a car" experience as a case study for fixed versus growth mindsets... i thought about saying this:
"i remember when i first learnt driving, i was pitiful, i didn't know whether to focus on the acceleration pedal, or the hand brakes or the other brakes or the vitesse or the side mirrors or rear mirrors, the thought of "driving is probably not my thing" has crossed my mind... and my lips, but um lucky i had friends around me who refused this message from me, they wouldn't allow me to utter it again and rebuke me for thinking about, i had to drive for 3 hours 6 days a week in one of the the cities with the worst traffic jams, i started with a professional driver beside me to take charge in case any emergency might happen, then i let him go, then my friend who started driving 5 years before myself would ride beside me to keep company , to point if someone is trying to double me... et voila...i have been driving for 6 years now, and um still alive thank God:) so, my point is... there is no "too late in learning",  and there's no "um not made for this" in learning either! I want you to throw any negative messages you received or negative approaches you adopted regarding your skills or talents academically behind your back today! Because the key thing is time and practice... & practice and time..."
I would appreciate peer feedback on this as much as ever!>
257:<LOL :)   I *did* notice that we have to "learn to grade things" for each and every assessment.>
258:<Not only do students place into remedial courses (I work with exactly those folks at a community college), but even the ones who do a little better on the placement tests don't understand the concepts; they just know the procedures. 
  I read an amazing article about that conceptual stuff called  What Community College Developmental Mathematics Students Understand About Mathematics ( http://www.carnegiefoundation.org/carnegie-perspectives/what-were-learning/what-community-college-developmental-mathematics-students-understand-about-math ) It includes an analysis of test scores showing  common errors   demonstrating a rather profound lack of basic understanding of concepts. Extensive interviews showed that students relied on memorized procedures (even when they got answers correct), rather than comprehension, and that K-12 instruction emphasizes procedures. Fortunately, a Key quote:
“…these students who have failed to learn mathematics in a deep and lasting way up to this point might be able to do so if we can convince them, first, that mathematics makes sense, and then provide them with the tools and opportunities to think and reason.”  And that's why I'm here :)>
