260:<I was first and foremost very interested in how the students interviewed were both enthusiastic about and confident in math.  It's like they felt they had learned some big secret about how to be successful later on!  I hope this success follows them -- they seem to regard fourth grade as a big scary thing, but they know how to handle it thanks to their heroic math teacher.

I'm a little surprised that they so freely say, "You can do what you want."  I think back to so many lunchtime conversations at my school among the math teachers absolutely *railing* at how students "invent" algebra.  "Don't they know there are rules for this sort of thing?!?"  It's not like these students will just do whatever they want, though; they appear to know that a decomposition or regrouping has to be right or useful, such as with the "friendly numbers."  I'd be interested to see if this is really the case.

Lastly, I'm surprised they call the teacher by his first name.  That would have resulted in some severe punishment when I was in elementary school.  :)>
261:<Indeed, mistakes help the individual in the act of learning to discover reality, to understand and realize the consequences of his mistake and to anticipate the risks involved.
Mistake should be part of learning. I have often led to solving a problem making a mistake results in order to verify the nurse's attention, the ability to make connections, knowledge and possibly comment on the result to defy logic. There were students asked me "but you know solving ?":)
There were those who did not accept mistakes while working. This has led to better understand my style of teaching and leave room for doubt before exclaim "I finished ...".
There are some professions where it is desirable not to make mistakes to learn from mistakes (doctor, aviator, scientist etc ...) even though that's exactly what happens. Analyze in detail why the causes of human error disasters.>
