264:<That's the question we will discuss. Most likely i first split the group in two's or three's to let them get some answers at first. After a few minutes involve the whole group.

I always point out that they are Mathematicians, you do not need to have to get an university degree first: for if you are a football player (a big thing for the boys) when you go to football/soccer every Saturday, then they are surely Mathematicians since they do maths every week with me! So they, as a smallish group of boys and girls (8-11 years old), are in this/belong together.

In the discussion I make sure several characteristics are discussed:
- precision (you need to know what you are trying to accomplish)
- creativity (you are supposed to create your own maths)
- the argument given is important, not who gives it
- It is more fun and quicker when you cooperate;
- A solution is only a solution if you can explain & defend it well.
 (esp. with proofs, this is obvious and also goes against many stereotypes) 
- reflecting on a solution or a mistake is the best way to learn more
  (in fact failing on purpose, and then reflecting on the why is a good general heuristic)

Afterwards we will discuss (and laugh at) some suggestions of what is not needed, usually:
- smart parent(s)
- a computer
- money
- glasses
- a blue skin
- boobs
- a turtle head
anything ridiculously stereotypical :)>
