273:<...the concrete things that numbers can represent.  Cards like this remind us that numerals represent quantities, and that combining quantities, an important basic skill, can be done in many ways.  The "shorthand" of using numerals and operations to combine quantities can represent an infinite list of things--  dots, apples, people, blades of grass, atoms, buckets of water, molecules of water, discussions, feelings...

With dot cards the focus is on the idea of quantities, and not on the numbers-- not on the written figures 3, 5, etc-- that the quantities represent.

I think this also reminds us that the concept of a number and the quantity it represents is incredibly broadly applicable, and in fact, I find it quite profound.  "Two-ness" ,"three-ness," "100-ness" can apply to blocks, handfuls of dirt, years of life, minutes, experiences... concrete things as well as abstract things...  So cool...:)>
