275:<I continually have discussions with my students about the fact that the point of being at school (and in life) is LEARNING THINGS, not being assessed on stuff. We talk a lot about why I don't provide revision sheets, why our assessment is always progressive and only summative when I can really not do anything about it. This term I have managed to clear my senior class of all assessment :D (by having worked ahead with them). They asked me why there was no assessment this term and I told them "this term we are just going to learn, not train for tests - what do you want to explore?" Getting answers right is no-where near as important as going on a learning journey. I hope this is the message I keep conveying to my students.>
276:<I always produce pep talks throughout the year that I get my students to read. They end up making fun of me but hey, so long as their mindset improves, no problem :). 
Here is an example:

**Mr <nameRedac_anon_screen_name_redacted>'s 'Pep Talk' Number 1**

**Make and share mistakes so that we make our learning better and become smarter.**

'In Mr. <nameRedac_anon_screen_name_redacted>'s Maths classes, we learn as a team.  Learning is messy and making mistakes is messy but don't worry as educational research says that this all makes our learning better and makes us smarter by growing our brain when things are wrong or are challenging.  Here are some success criteria to help us to improve our learning together. Remember to:

 1. Always make deliberate and thoughtful attempts so that you are able to justify, reason or explain to me or others the learning in your head.
 2. Study your mistakes so that you learn to pinpoint the learning problem, and can begin to see how to improve them.
 3. Be happy and willing to share your mistakes so that other members of the team may learn from them too; be selfless.
 4. Be respectful and attentive to others mistakes so that our team is not afraid to share mistakes and be able to learn from them another time.
 5. Only give critical but constructive feedback that improves learning. Make it honest but respectful so that they will offer ideas another time.
 6. Read the three quotes below if you're ever worried about making mistakes:

Thomas Edison (1879) – inventor of the light bulb amongst other things:

> I am not discouraged, because every wrong attempt discarded is another step forward.

And Einstein said:

> Anyone who has never made a mistake has never tried anything new.

And lastly, Samuel Beckett, writer and winner of the Nobel Prize for Literature (1969)

> Ever tried. Ever failed. No matter. Try Again. Fail again. Fail better.>
