281:<I always have different ideas for these types of questions and although I have already answered in the task section I've just seen another. By the way, they look like cans to me rather than cubes.  Maybe I'll use those in class! :-)

Start with the first case.  We could take a single can and put it on top of the other single can to create a square.  We now have a square of side 2 thus there are 2^2=4 cans.
We could also use the idea that (case <zipRedac> + <zipRedac>)^2 = 4

In the second case we can create a square of side 3 which will give us 3^3=9 cans.
We could also use the idea that (case 2 + <zipRedac>)^2 = 9

We can repeat this for any case.
We now know that the number of cans in any case, let's call it n, will always be the square of <zipRedac> more than the case; this is because we have rearranged the original shapes into squares.

So for case n, the number of cans = (n+<zipRedac>)^2

And for <zipRedac>00 cases, the number of cans = (<zipRedac>00+<zipRedac>)^2 = <zipRedac>020<zipRedac> cans.>
