287:<Grouping has never made any sense to me. I have chosen to never be a part of it. I left teaching for years because of it and am now working with home learning children where this issue rarely arises.  My own children are autodidacts and self motivated learners.( 2 of them never went to school) and - without even knowing it- I supported a growth mind set in them. As adults they are now fully functioning and engaged members of society - passionately doing their own thing.

The other thing that has never made sense to me is grouping based on age. (ie 6 years old means grade 1.) So often this equates to socialization with only your particular age group..... and this happens NOWHERE ELSE in society. As an adult, I have many friends - older and younger - with a variety of educational backgrounds. What we share in common are interests and passions. I think children should be allowed the same freedom of association.

I guess I am "outside the box" on this one.... :)>
