298:<I feel the same way. After I do the lesson and before I call a group, I walk around and watch the student's do their independent work. I try to pull students who I noticed were struggling on the current lesson first.  This is not the same set of students every time. Then I try to call over as many students as I can before the " exit ticket time.  I was not sure if this was the right way to do it. But if there are more than 5 students who are struggling I may assign a mentor. Now I am questioning the way I do it. I feel like I am grouping them without the title of the group.???  :( The students who do their independent work are able to grade their own work with the answer key, with a different color pen and then are asked to hand it in before they can work on center work.  The centers are student choices.  I have a tick tac toe board every week with different tasks they can accomplish. It ranges from "review" work to Challenge activities.  If the student wants to get a tic tac toe for the week they HAVE TO COMPLETE a challenge activity. This can be done with a buddy of their choice or independently.  At the end of the week all students have to make one tic tac toe for "credit" and then if they wanted to try to get more than one tic tac toe it is worth more.  :)  It become as a fun game for my students and they have the ability to work at a level of their choice and be challenged.>
299:<(I posted this in the wrong place & then couldn't find it to move it! Sorry if it's in here twice)
OMG! Here's the evolution of my thought on this problem:

 1. (Stalling a bit while telling myself this is not for a grade)
 2. Yikes! She's making me do math? I haven't a clue! 
 3. Oh. There's that Fixed Mindset thing, huh.
 4. Started counting the number of cubes in each case. Not seeing a pattern, other than the one in the picture I cannot yet articulate.
 5. Started writing the total cubes for each case and extending the pattern to case 4 and case 5. Still not seeing anything. Slight panic setting in--- instinct to "look up the answer". Beat down this feeling by remembering that it's supposed to be challenging. I'm growing my math brain.
 6. Since the pattern in the totals was not obvious to me, decided to see how the totals were increasing. From 4 to 9 is 5; from 9 to 16 is 7; from 16 to 25 is 9; from 25 to 36 is 11. 
 7. Oh, look. A pattern. 5, 7, 9, 11....  
 8. So I don't have to painstakingly draw or write out 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1  etc. on each one. I can use the pattern to find the totals. (there must be a shorter way.... I'll work on that later)
 9. I made a chart, with boxes for cases 1-10 in the top row. I wrote the totals I had so far, and in-between the boxes, a little triangle with the odd numbers increasing in the pattern I already noticed. I then filled in the rest of the totals by using those odd numbers. I continued this process, with a row for cases 11- 20 and  a row for 21 - 30, and looked again for patterns. I noticed that in the "9s" column the totals were even hundreds. Then I noticed that all the cases in the first column ended in 4, second column all ended in 9, 3rd column all ended in 6 etc. Don't know how that helps me yet, but it's interesting.  Then I noticed, looking at the 9th column, the hundreds went from 100, 400, 900... I wonder if the next one will be 1600, since the first totals were 4, 9, 16. I'll do another row and see.
 10.  Yes! And now I know how to figure the rest. Going down just row 9, continuing the pattern of totals and the pattern of odd numbers, box 99 will be 10,000--- so the total for case 100 will be 10,201.
 11. Answering backward-- for the first question,  "How do [I] see this shape growing." The stacks per case are growing by odd numbers-- 3, 5, 7, 9 etc.
 12. I've never smiled while doing a difficult (for me) math problem before. :-D Now I'm curious to know how to do this a shorter wa>
