311:<I remember discussing that equals sign as a balance. It's hard to convey, though, especially to students who not only conceptually think equals means "points at the answer" (and http://olms.cte.jhu.edu/olms/data/resource/9231/Why%20Cant%20Students%20Get%20Concept%20Math_Week%2010.pdf  describes this (I can't seem to make this a working link..  -- the whole International Dyslexia Assoc. "math" issue is online at http://www.resourceroom.net/Math/perspectives_dyslexia_math.pdf ) 
... and *especially* to my students who've developed some incredible visual imitation strategies that almost always work... until algebra. 

    One lady at a conference described success with having students draw a little "balance of justice" over the equals sign.   I had a student that I noticed drawing a dashed vertical line from the equals sign to help separate those two sides that were supposed to balance.   I've stolen and shared madly :) 

   Another strategy that we used in our short, intense "conceptual foudnations" class and will be trying out with the pre-pre-algebra folks is that we can call the same thing two different things... and still be talking about the same thing.  Another thing we're trying to do is to have a "fault-resistant" class, so I've been scrapping together narrated powerpoints for folks who miss a class or want a review, and http://www.resourceroom.net/math/roughvids/1equalsmeansnomic.pptx  is my rough for "what equals means."   It's very validating to see similar things expressed here! 


