361:<So this is a pretty rough/first draft, but I think it has potential. :)

First, have students create statements that they have heard, been told, said to themselves or to a friend or would like to hear when they work (when they make a mistake).  Some examples may include  “I believe you can change your intelligence, or “I like working hard to learn something new”, “I would rather do something easy and not make mistakes than work hard to learn something new”, or “You cannot change how smart you are.” 

Have students write down a few statements that are applicable to what they believe.

Then, pairs/triples of students separate (categorize) the statements and give each group a title/name.

Share out with the class/large group about how and why they decided to separate the statements and why they chose their title.

Then, share a powerpoint (like http://www.laurelschool.org/about/documents/BrainTraining.pdf) or a reading (like http://www.mindsetworks.com/websitemedia/youcangrowyourintelligence.pdf) about Fixed and Growth mindset.  

Have students revisit their statement groups and determine whether they aligned to fixed/growth mindsets or something else. Have small groups pair up with other small groups for the discussion.

Finally, have students determine whether they are currently at a Fixed or Growth Mindset and write a few phrases that encourage the Growth mindset whether or not they are currently there.>
