363:<I'm trying something different, perhaps a bit cheeky. Not sure if it works - read the learning goals first before the big reveal:

We are looking at numbers like 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, ... and so on. These are called 'natural numbers', but we'll just say 'numbers' for now. If you know about negative numbers, then just try to forget them for now :-)

Goals:

1. I understand that any number always has just one other number that is one bigger than it. The bigger number is called the 'successor' of the other number.

2. I understand that there is a number called 'zero' that is not one bigger than any number. So, it's not the successor of any other number.

3. I understand that if I can't see two numbers, but I know they have the same successor, then those two number must be the same number.

4. I understand that, if we make a collection of numbers that has zero in it, and we make sure every number in the collection also has its successor in the collection, then that collection contains all numbers (0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, ... and so on).

You could call this 'axiomatic number theory for kids' :-) This is a rewriting of the Peano Axioms of axiomatic number theory in a phenomenological way. Seems obvious? Perhaps it's *too* obvious and easily overlooked. If the above makes sense, then you are well on your way to understanding the basis of all modern number theory .. and perhaps you'll pause to wonder why numbers exist in our universe at all.>
