404:<I have great sympathy for the challenges of teaching a diverse group of kids, but I think the fixed mindset imposed includes a mindset that a certain amount of material must be plowed through with the teacher doing all the teaching. I think it is very powerful when a student that "gets it" has the opportunity to express their thinking - how they worked a problem and worked through whatever difficulties. The examples of "flipping the classroom" may seem extreme to some folks as well, but there are elements of that approach that allows classroom time to be spent in inquiry and offers more opportunity to discuss and share. When a student has an opportunity to "teach" that is a challenge that isn't normally available, and if the parents are pushing for challenge for their gifted-talented, I would think that would cover it. Not only will it deepen the students understanding who hear the presentation, the student "teaching" will see more insights from articulating his/her process. [Jake Barnett is an autistic boy who is I think 13 now, and a student of astrophysics at Indiana U; I saw him draw out about 70 zeros to show his brothers the benefits of scientific notation; he seems to be a natural teacher :-)]>
