409:<I was thinking I would open with the fact we learned that successful people make MORE mistakes. Hopefully that will take some of the fear of "doing it wrong" away. Then we can talk about the positive effects that making a mistake and going through the process of learning from a mistake has. We can talk about how everyone makes mistakes and that mistakes are process, perhaps using the quote (paraphrased and probably misattributed to Edison) "I have not failed; I have merely found 10,000 ways that don't work."
<br>
We could also go over the MISTAKES poster I made earlier, and talk about mistakes we've made in our lives (mathematical and otherwise) and how they have helped us learn and grow as people.
 <br> 
We would then talk about my positive feelings about mistakes, and how I like it when my students make mistakes because then I know they are learning and I can use those mistakes to help other students learn. I can also ask them to be positive about the mistakes their peers make, remembering that mistakes help not only the person having them (better than if no mistake was made) but also those around them who can take the opportunity to learn from the mistakes of their friends, too.
<br>
Hopefully all of this will create a comfortable culture of mistake-making in my classroom, so that students are able to take risks freely and make mistakes positively. :)>
