I've been thinking a lot about the "how does this shape grow" problem presented earlier in the course and how I could deploy this with kids to help them see patterns. I thought of one exercise that you may find helpful -- my daughter is ten and totally loves "thought experiments" that have to do with her stuffed animals -- so we have a party and they all "happen to like beans" so we have to decide about how many each animal would like, since they are all different sizes and eat different amounts, so we could play this out by getting a 1 or 2 lb bag of dried beans and letting her separate the amounts she thinks would be sufficient in different piles, then that leads to a discussion about different ways of getting to different amounts..(we could even image bigger animals not in the group she has that would need even bigger amounts)..I also tell her when I'm taking a class (I'm a librarian so she knows I'm always into finding stuff) and that I need a kid's perspective on how to be more flexible in my own thinking (she loves that and is happy to help when I put myself in the learner's position)...>
