439:<Kids have a tendency to think that whatever way the teacher answers the question is the best or correct way to answer and if the student thought differently they will think their method is not effective or that it is even wrong.  By sharing different methods or approaches a child can see that there are many different ways of doing math effectively and finstead of feeling that they did it the wrong way they will feel validated that their way was an acceptable way (because there is clearly more than one way of answering) and they may feel encouraged to try seeing numbers/problems differently instead of defending their thought process. And the brilliant icing on the cake, is that the teacher can facilitate a conversation that students will draw these conclusions from instead of telling them the conclusion which will make many students more receptive (some don't mind just being told :)>
