461:<All too often when I see a cool idea that I want to start using in my middle grade classrooms I jump in head first and expect things to go as smoothly as they did when I either saw them done or participated in them! With this example of the dot cards as a beginning step to working with number talks, students would have the chance to practice the process before the math was challenging. The teacher can use something like this to lay the groundwork for how number talks are used, how the discussions flow, how students need to be clear when explaining their thinking, and how connections can be made throughout a variety of methods. I'm looking forward to trying out a dot card number talk later this week :)>
462:<Sounds like a good idea :)  Let us know how it turns out.  I agree with you that I was tracked as gifted and bored if I wasn't in an advanced class.  What we really need is to unschool completely.  Schools should be completely open and optional, so the students can choose to enroll only in topics that they are actually wanting to learn and ready to learn.  Then all learning will take place quickly and efficiently and painlessly.  It's a matter of choice.  Of course, this doesn't mean that some people won't struggle with their learning.  A lot of people enjoy doing things that they aren't necessarily good at.  But if you enroll people of different ages and abilities in a class, like a knitting class, the more experienced and talented of the group will automatically become additional peer teachers who help the newcomers.  That is what real learning should always look like.  You got your grannies sitting next to the new mommies next to the teenagers.  Why should math be any different?>
463:<Sounds good to me :)  I'm looking at what learning looked like before we started compulsory education, the great social experiment, only about 150 years ago in the US.  I don't know why in a few short generations, we have all forgotten how to learn and how to teach.  Learning is supposed to be fun, not work.  Teaching is a social thing.  You can learn things by yourself, too, but most people like to have someone else who's good at something show them.  Take our minds out of the school box, and imagine how Alice might have learned her lessons before she fell into her Wonderland daydream.  What happened to our apprenticeships?  What happened to having lunch with your family?  Society has gone terribly awry in taking children away from their families and putting them in institutions to learn to "socialize" with each other.  How did people ever learn to be social and have manners before school came along?>
