475:<There is largely a "setting" system in place at my high school.There is a "top-set" and a "Support" set in every year group and then the remaining classes are "mixed'. The interesting thing is, that I find I need to differentiate every lesson (I have at least one of each of the above classes). I do not have one class where "everyone's at the same place all the time". Every student comes with a different understanding and the best bit is when we start a topic and we find out what everyone else knows. I love the fact that I don't have classes of robots! The hard part to come to terms with, is the idea that these kids "know their set", so they would be receiving messages about their ability from the "setting", but hopefully not from my teaching and their learning :).>
