520:<This is the exact dilemma I am having in my classroom right now. How do I teach all my students when tests have shown them to range from 2nd to 9th grade levels. We are a huge "intervention" school since we are Title 1. We pull kids out of electives for extra math and have a mandatory tutoring hour (where  the non tutoring kids get to play games and do fun things). I can't control this. I can only control my classroom (to an extent). What I'm realizing is that I have been failing to differentiate at all. And all these other teachers and parents ARE right, it's hard. It's to change tasks, assessments, and mindsets, too, but we've got to figure out how to do it. Right now I suppose I'm reconsidering my in class intervention plan, wondering if I should still target groups of kids who have been deemed "in need of intervention"... so essentially- I'm lost and in survival mode. :)>
521:<I loved hearing that math is free and you can do what you want!  I also was happy to hear that sometimes we make mistakes but everyone makes mistakes. :)>
522:<I've already started the year asking the question, "who here would like to have a bigger brain by June?"  My kids, who are ESL all looked shocked by my question put their hands up.  I explained how mistakes create two synapses (drew the brain and zaps on the whiteboard) to make the connections stronger and the brain grow bigger...and that's why I like mistakes. I also added, if I choose you, it may be bc we can all learn from your mistake.  I use the "bzzz' sound to symbolize brain growth, the kids know is and use it too :)>
